Subject: ggml_extend: cancellation checkpoint at the top of compute()

Adds a single `pretty_progress(0, 0, 0)` call at the entry to the
GGMLRunner `compute()` template. Since every model runner (CLIP, T5,
UNet, VAE, ControlNet, ESRGAN, ...) goes through this template, this
turns the entire heavy-compute path into a cancellation point — not
just the sampling-step boundary the upstream `pretty_progress` calls
already cover.

Why this works as-is:

  - `pretty_progress(0, 0, 0)` with no progress callback registered
    bails on the `step == 0` early-return in util.cpp's pretty_progress
    body. No spurious stdout.

  - With a callback registered, the callback is invoked with
    (step=0, steps=0, time=0). node-stable-diffusion-cpp's CCallback
    runs its abort check unconditionally and then drops the (0,0,0)
    sentinel before dispatching to JS, so the JS-side progress feed
    stays clean — only real sampler/VAE-tile events surface.

This is the minimum invasive change that makes:
  - conditioning (CLIP / T5 / clip_g chunks) cancellable
  - tokenizer/embedder forward passes cancellable
  - VAE encode (img2img init) cancellable
  - upscaler/ESRGAN cancellable
  - every per-step cond/uncond/skip-layer compute cancellable

…all by adding cancellation latency of "one in-flight ggml graph
compute" everywhere instead of "one sampling step on the diffusion
model" only.

